  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 26.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Ramah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Now er-Ram. This would seem, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 31:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and from a comparison of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Jeremiah 40:1, to have been the Ramah of later history, famous as the dwelling place of Samuel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc., for Mount Ephraim is applied to territory in Benjamin. Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 20:1, 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was near Gibeah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 10:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and not far from Bethel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was rebuilt by Baasha (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 15:17, 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Mizpeh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is the Mizpeh, or Mizpah, of Benjamin, whither the tribes were wont to gather together, and where the tabernacle appears to have been removed (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:1, 3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 21:1-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). If, as Lieut. Conder supposes, Nob and Mizpeh were identical, and were near Jerusalem, this would explain the presence of the tribes within the border of Benjamin on this occasion. They were near the border; and the Benjamites had retired to their mountain fastnesses. This seems almost implied in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Similar gatherings are recorded in the Book of Samuel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 7:5-7, 11, 12, 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 10:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Mizpeh was the seat of Gedaliah's administration, and of the tragedy of his assassination (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:23-25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 40:10-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). Joshua 18:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Mizpeh, commonly called Mizpah, where the war with Benjamin was decided upon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and where Samuel judged the people, and chose Saul as king (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 10:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), was afterwards the seat of the Babylonian governor Gedaliah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 40:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). According to the Onom. (s. v. Massepha), it was near Kirjath-jearim, and Robinson (ii. p. 139) is no doubt correct in supposing it to be the present Neby Samvil (i.e., prophet Samuel), an hour and a quarter to the east of Kureyet Enab (Kirjath-jearim), two hours to the north-west of Jerusalem, half an hour to the south of Gibeon, a place which stands like a watch-tower upon the highest point in the whole region, and with a mosque, once a Latin church, which is believed alike by Jews, Christians, and Mahometans to cover the tomb of the prophet Samuel (see Rob. ii. pp. 135ff.). Chephirah, i.e., Kefir: see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 9:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Mozah is only mentioned here, and is still unknown. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 18:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This also applies to Rekem, Irpeel, and Taralah.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]